Architects have understood that offices also need day care
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the Arch.Design company.
No one would say that it also hides a small nursery in its interior with everything itself to such facilities: colored walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the sons of the employees of Arch.Design can come to her.
The architectonic project company Arch.Design, whose study came out of numerous known buildings of Brno, thought from the first drafts of the building Avriopoint to include a space for its mini-guard.
The company works around 90 people, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, daycare is one of the benefits that Arch.Designs his workers as part of his social program.
Constructors and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with child care.
The mini-guard was an idea of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-guard is financed through the European Social Fund within the framework of the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment, as well as the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to funding (a total of more than 2.8 million Czech crowns) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When funding is exhausted (two years), Arch.Design has an obligation to keep the mini-guardy running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and in the submission of the request for funding contributed to the company Economy Rating.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, a nurse and a teacher of the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day day-to-day care is provided to children without age limit, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since this is a "mini-storey", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children at the same time, even if the shifts come more during the day.
The operation of the day-care facility is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the day-care facility, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is individual education and care, the contents of the mini-guard programme are comparable to the usual pre-school curriculum.
In it children not only play, but also receive a quality education: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach up to English.
The class has not only toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their place of work.
Thus, parents are more productive as they work.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the sign companies that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened the marketing of staff.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. See the interiors of Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals called it "the house of bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the novel use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade that reminds the scales and omnipresent gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with oniric lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, there is a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thoughted order.
At night, the whole facade of the house seems even more impressive, as it is illuminated so that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpent and the twist of forms continues to surprise us also inside it.
Corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the brooms, the ornaments of the doors, the mirrors and the signs.
The Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample neighborhood in number 43 of Passeig de Grácia's lively shopping street, emerged from the remodeling of a house in 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the rich industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on bringing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of making a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in their plans of the project, ornaments emerged for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Milá House and the Güell de Gaudí park, where other parts of it are found.
Due to its organic form, the premises soon after their completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific opening mechanism of the windows began to call it "the house of the woods".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia appears.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation ventilators and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange its inclination of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not at all respect the construction rules of the moment and did not allow himself to be influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although obviously in it the data indicated on the expected reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so impressed by the result it requested to be corrected.
He was upset, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public yard.
The arrangements were never made, but on the contrary: only fifteen days after the city council request, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
The owner himself was installed on the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-storey house is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the living rooms and a larger group can thus communicate without any problems, without giving up the necessary privacy for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with both colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which instead absorb sun rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment of the accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits, they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and expanded visits to the common area and to the Butterfly, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get 20% discount.
The amount significantly exceeds the price of entering other Gaudí buildings in the city.
