Increasingly parents use tracking devices to control their children
Fear for children keeps more and more people thinking about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in case the nine-year-old girl Anička Janatková disappeared.
For the moment the device has the approximate size of a box of eyeglasses, but will soon be reduced to the size of a clock.
Many people were afraid of the missing Anička case and began to report on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
"We all try to tell ourselves that it is not about spying, but about another means of reducing the chances of a tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the providers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they are put in someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not yet encountered such cases."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," adds Pilin.
In your opinion, children should always know what the "cajita" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns about the fact that if the child does not want to take it, he will simply throw it away.
"Even younger children show great creativity when they intentionally lose certain things if they want to avoid being controlled."
"Before, parents relied heavily on mobile phones, but they could be turned off as easily as the tracking device," says Bočková.
In your opinion, it is questionable whether such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
"If it is a prepared kidnapping, the author will practically always check whether the child has any type of electronic device that can reveal its location."
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices is being extended, it will also look for them, since their sale will certainly be made with much publicity."
"In such cases, offenders always go one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, it adds that such devices can help in the event of an improvised attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of the RC Monitoring company, which provides follow-up services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is destroyed immediately, its presence can be helpful.
"The device can be configured to regularly send the position after a certain period."
"If you suffer damage, at least it will facilitate the last position of the person in question."
"The most expensive devices incorporate a tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and stays motionless, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," says Čech.
