Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as well as support for private enterprises.
Crime is more of a concern than unemployment.
In addition, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the findings of the last Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
As the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it is possible to monitor changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related issues were highlighted in the results of this year's survey in September and early October.
The first is the relatively animated mood reigning in Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the South American Pacific coast (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6 per cent annually since 2002, support for democracy has increased from 40% in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
He also grew up in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after a great decline in production last year.
However, only half of the respondents from Mexico and Brazil, the two most populated countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see figure 2).
Around 44 per cent of respondents in the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but significantly higher than 25 per cent in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34 per cent said they trusted the Congress of their country and 45 per cent in their Government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but significantly higher than in 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turmoil in Latin America seriously affected support for democracy.
The fact that it was maintained during the global financial crisis is likely due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social security network has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty is only marginally increasing in 2009 and has been reduced again this year to 32 per cent.)
However, the mood varies considerably from country to country (see figure 4).
The good economic performances of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
This feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more serious and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the start of the surveys, most polled in Latin America mention crime, instead of unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see figure 5).
About 31 per cent said that they or close relatives had been victims of crime in the last year, a figure that had been reduced since 38 per cent last year and that had been the lowest percentage since 1995.
The most positive economic returns are reflected in increased support for private enterprises and the market economy: around 71 per cent of respondents in the region claim that private enterprises are indispensable for development, while in 2007 only 56 per cent (see figure 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will enable their country to develop, compared to 47% last year.
It is interesting that 62% of respondents in Venezuela feel the same way (and 80% support private companies), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country that exercises greater leadership in the region, as indicated by 19 per cent of respondents (up from 18 per cent last year), followed by the United States (9 per cent, same as last year) and Venezuela (9 per cent versus 11 per cent a year ago).
However, the United States is the country considered most influential by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds this title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
