An arsenic-resistant microbial raises the possibility of new forms of life on Earth... or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients broadens the possibility of finding new forms of life on Earth and, possibly, on other planets.
Although researchers discovered the curious bacterium here on Earth, they say it shows that there may be life forms without the main elements they considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity."
"It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"That makes it a very peculiar thing, although it lacks little to be a really 'alienogenic' form of life," said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report that appears in the online edition of the publication Science.
For a long time, there have been six major elements essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
However, researchers have discovered that the bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you wonder how much more is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
As Anbar pointed out, finding is important for the search for life on different planets on Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the call for a press conference to discuss it, in which details of the discovery were not disclosed, generated a great speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report would indicate the discovery of alien life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "if it shows is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of "standard" elements that we consider essential for life may not be so fixed," said Charles Cockell, Professor of Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates the replacement of one element by another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure," Cockell added.
The discovery was not by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who conducted the study, focused on the Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so it speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace one another.
"Arsenic is mainly toxic because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus."
"Consequently, it may be difficult for organisms to differentiate them."
"However, the arsenic is different enough so it doesn't work as well as the phosphorus, so it comes in and somehow calls the biochemical machinery," explains Anbar.
Researchers collected bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing arsenic concentrations, which they managed to adapt and use to grow.
The microbial grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that it can naturally exist a form of life that uses arsenic, whether in other parts of the Earth or on another planet or moon where the arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, indicated that the idea that arsenic can be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but an example had never been found that proved to work.
The arsenic was more common in early Earth eras, he pointed out, so researchers speculated that the first forms of life could have used it.
"Yes, it suggests that there could be other means of generating life, not only the way life was formed on Earth in the past," Foster said, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and National Health Institutes.
