Interviews, e-mails and other documents that first appeared in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain lucrative work through lobbying, to achieve Hampton's silence and his wife, Cynthia, on the Senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as a treasurer of an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find work for Mr Hampton and advocated on behalf of them after they had hired Mr Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
