Ethics experts said that the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were intimate friends before the affair, appeared in disagreement with the so-called "revolving door lobbying ban", which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections to do personal business.
Of the evidence that has been made public, "it seemed to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolting door status," said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
