Can civics hold a bridge to join divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invective and negativity, this week a little civilism has been unleashed in Washington.
Is it an omen of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a rapid return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and the leaders of Congress did not make any progress on the major issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But from what they all say, it was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to rule, rather than being another empty episode to win partisan points.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the President's deficit commission was also civilised, despite the political differences that remain among the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months has generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is just enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has come.
Both sides are now in a period of testing, investigating each other to identify signs of cooperativeism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the voter's patience for a renewed partisan war.
The reason why Tuesday ' s meeting and subsequent evaluations of it by participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too great and deeply rooted as to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is tax, expenditure, health care or social assistance, the two sides are located in opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened humor in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with regard to how to say things," said Pete Wehner, an official of the Bush administration now at the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"They are inevitable after the elections.
Elections awaken biases, which are then extinguished.
That's good."
In some matters, in particular those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax reductions are due at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to extend unemployment subsidies, probably because Republicans cannot believe that they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, denying the unemployment benefit for the unemployed.
After Tuesday's meeting in the White House, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, together with the ratification of the new START Nuclear Disarmament Pact (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation in the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanism when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He stated, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement begins.
"After the things that must be done are carried out, in the short term psychology will turn the situation to a confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed scepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civicism can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a trial for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons have much to do with the establishment of the new Republican majority in the House and the members of the Tea Party, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as the Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know that they should try to fulfill their promises to cut state expenses and cancel the new health law.
These lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include the reform of the tax code and the increase in some taxes and retirement age, and the reduction of expenditure.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have been responsible for one of the most difficult work in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forcibly introduced the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The highest resistance is among the elected officers in the panel, suggesting that there are at least few bases or wish for commitment in tax matters.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and those of Congress.
The first will take place next year in the form of partisan shocks, when Republicans challenge Obama's budget, taxes and medical assistance, followed by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanism of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks he's probably losing will change course and seek compromise.
However, this can be an optimistic vision.
Partyism and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Congress Republicans than between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common points on issues that still divide them.
