Early next year, the court is expected to begin prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former minister of the Red Jemeres.
The court's mandate is to prosecute the main leaders and those of greater responsibility for crimes, but it has not said whether it will prosecute cases in addition to those four.
This did not serve much to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
The recent media speculation has focused on 64-year-old Im Chaem, who was a district chief in the province of Banteay Meanchey during the government of the Red Jemeres in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Center that she had supervised the construction of Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced workers are thought to have died.
During a recent booming afternoon, Im Chaem once again worked in the fields at his house on wooden balls on a dirt road on the outskirts of Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows on the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Red Jemeres.
She claimed that if the court called her, she wouldn't show up.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable," he said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who deserted Red Jemers in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there would be instability if the court pursued more suspects, although experts and historians questioned him.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But facing the past is exactly what Cambodia must do to move forward, said Chhang Youk, from the documentation center.
"Reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to rejoin broken pieces," he said.
"It is our obligation to gather these broken pieces so that we can understand."
The centre produced the first book approved by the government on the Red Jemeres, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea", 75 pages.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the secondary school history book of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages about the Red Jemeres.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know little about the Red Jemeres, despite the link between the city and the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19 years old, a student at the Anlong Veng High School, said that the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their history.
But their parents reacted skeptically when they took the book home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the text book and the court," he said.
"They have suspicions because they are not sure about the number of people who will prosecute the court."
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the textbook and the court are beginning to have an impact, he said.
