EU changes rules for visas
People must attend Visa Applicant Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and as well as the waiting time.
As from 10 January 2011, the procedure for processing a visa at the United States Embassy and consulates will be changed.
Under the new procedure, most applicants are required to attend Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASCs) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
ASC staff shall take the biometric information of the applicant, which shall be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer required to make a payment to conclude the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment that will cover the three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Those who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest AUC where they will present their documents and take their marks.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken into the AUC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in this less time than in the past.
Similarly, those applying for visas in the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra fee of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
