Hackers vengeful and diligent spies
WikiLeaks has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that just seems to scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at international level and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file created by a secret service (independent of the nation to which it belongs) consists exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Khadafi's sinisterly ridiculous profile has long been giving cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The norm that secret records should only be formed by news of public knowledge is essential for the dynamics of secret services, not only in this century.
If you visit a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to the occult not only trust what they already know, which confirms what they have already learned.
This is Dan Brown's success mechanism.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little anxiety) the head of the secret services (if it could not be, I know, editor of the Liberation), which only considers certain what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that sent the American Embassy of Rome to the State Department was the same as the Newsweek published the previous week.
Why, then, have such revolts caused the revelations of these records?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, i.e., that embassies, at least since World War II and since Heads of States can be called by telephone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic role and, with the exception of a few limited exercises of representation, have become spy centres.
Any viewer who sees research films knows it perfectly, we just seem to know that we don't know it for hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that a hacker could consult the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "verdugues".
But we enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Previously, in Orwell's time, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother controlling every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, being able to control each movement thanks to the phone, each transaction performed, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a full victim of the power eye.
But when it is demonstrated, as now, that not even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the revenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer retain its own secrets be sustained?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge of Berlusconi or Merkel's character is actually an empty, unsecret secret, since it comes from the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to take away all power.
