It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the network, as it would be like publishing it on a road map.
But it is also clear that confidential telephone conversations cannot be expected with current technologies.
Nothing is easier than discovering whether and when a Head of State has moved by plane and has contacted one of the counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relations in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my forecast is science fiction and, therefore, novice, but I imagine government agents who quietly move in diligence with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, at most, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
This information is then kept, in a single copy, in closed drawers with key: in the end, the attempt to spy on Watergate was less successful than WikiLeaks.
