Climate: France's hats in its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the fast-disbursed funding pledges (called fast-start or early) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French carpets have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union undertook to contribute 7.2 billion euros in three years and France 1.260 million euros (i.e. 420 million euros per year).
During the opening of the COP16, the EU has placed its best letters on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was appreciable and was appreciated for what really matter: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2.2 billion, which puts it on the right track towards fulfilling its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without damaging official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each one chooses the reference that best suits him.
For example, the European Commission has made reference to 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years as fast-start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development aid.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, it does not refer to expenditure in previous years or to the total level of official development aid.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), while it seeks to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the sharing between donations and loans.
Once again, there is no standard and each one chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that each euro lent is equivalent to a euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain profitable investments (often projects related to reducing emissions based on more effective technologies), it is false to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... At a large level, only the cost of the loan for the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent of a interest rate) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: "respect" its commitment of EUR 420 million making 91.5% loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (EUR 36.1 million); see the EU document to see it for its own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union which uses the loan so often.
Germany uses it by 46 per cent, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union provides a euro to meet its commitment, France only provides ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start funding, France does double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions in time and on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, it can give the impression that it spends 420 million "new and additional", as it had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has been involved in arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why were the other Member States still giving when they could just lend?) and in negotiations, since developing countries are not stupid...
The chapter on early financing is a short-term detail in relation to all climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But in particular, France could move forward the discussions on the stakes in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is with others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive at Cancún next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of the "additional character" and the use of loans would help improve the level of international confidence needed to advance negotiations.
